Preheat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root, peel and chop into roughly 1cm pieces. Cut the top off the @aubergine{1}, then cut in half lengthways. Slice each half into thin strips and then chop into roughly 1cm pieces.

Put your veggies in a deep #baking tray{} with high sides, drizzle over a good glug of @oil{1%glug}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a really good grind of @black pepper{pinch}. Sprinkle over the @smoked paprika{1/2%tsp} and give it all a good shake until everything is nicely coated in spice and oil. Put the baking tray on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%minutes}, until your veggies are soft.

While your veggies are cooking, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1/2%bunch} and drain and rinse the @butter beans{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

Season each @haddock fillet{2} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{pinch} on both side.

When your onion and aubergine have been cooking for 20-25 mins, remove from your oven and add the @tomato passata{1%400g} along with your butter beans and half your parsley. Season with another pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{pinch}. Stir everything together and put back in your oven for ~{5%minutes}.

Drizzle some @oil{1%tbsp} into a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-high heat. When the pan is hot add your fish, skin-side down.

> Tip: Don't move the fish when it's cooking skin-side down or it won't get a crispy skin!

Cook for ~{3-4%minutes} then turn over and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> Tip: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

When everything is ready, take your aubergine and butter bean stew out of your oven and spoon into #bowls{}. Place your haddock on top, sprinkle over your remaining parsley and enjoy!